t-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Commission starts from the position that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">all </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eligible electors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should, as far as is possible, be treated equally. If </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">were given the right to vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">this principle should also apply to them</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he specific circumstances of convicted prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mean that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> certain processes available to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">other </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">electors would not be practical or desirable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to apply to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> prisoners</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Allowing prisoners to vote at polling stations would rarely</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> be a practical option, for example.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We see no reason why a prisoner </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be treated any differently to any other voter who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is unable to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">attend a polling station</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cast their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be able either to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vote by post or appoint a proxy. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">voting by post </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">retain </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the right to a secret ballot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we believe that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">here </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would need to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be a requirement for prisons to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ensure this.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We also believe that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">risoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have the same right to regist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> anonymously</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as any other </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">elector</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">dministrative impact of giving prisoners the right to vote</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:14.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We do not believe </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">risoners should be registered at the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> address</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">where they are detained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Nor do we believe that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prison governors </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should be required </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to complete a canvass of all prisoners</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. To do so</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would impose a significant and unnecessary administrative burden on them </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">because </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the information collected would need to be sent to all of the relevant Electoral Registration Officers (EROs) across the country.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ome prisoners are frequently moved around the country and this would significantly exacerbate the potential burden upon prison bureaucracy as a whole.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Instead, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eligible prisoners should be required to register either at the address where they would normally be living or a previous address, rather than at the address of the facility where they are being held. This would be similar to other categories of elector (including service personnel and Crown servants) who are required to be absent from their normal residential address for a significant period of time</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who are able to register </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">either </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">at a previous address or the address at which they would be living, were they not based overseas. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We expect that t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he prison service (including the Scottish Prison Service, and Northern Ireland Prison Service) would need to take some responsibility for ensuring that eligible electors in prison had information about how to register to vote. This would require the allocation of suitable resources to the prison service, although we would expect that the Commission would have a role in providing advice and guidance on the kind of information that would be helpful.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If the eligibility of individual prisoners to register to vote were to be dependent on the specific circumstances of their imprisonment (such as the length of their term of imprisonment), we expect that any application to register would need to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">verified or ‘attested’ by a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">member of prison staff</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> so that an ERO </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> able to determine whether or not the application should be granted. We do not believe it would be appropriate for any eligible prisoner to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prevented from registering to vote </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">because of the refusal of prison staff to attest their application to register. The prison services, inspectorates and ombudsmen across the UK should ensure that those able to attest a declaration are under a clear duty to do so.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If electoral registration applications by prisoners were required to be supported by special attestations, the annual canvass form sent to households would not need to collect the names of previous residents who are currently in prison. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The level or grade of prison staff </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would be authorised to attest these applications could be prescribed, as it is for certain police ranks in relation to anonymous registration. The prescribed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">grade</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should be low enough that the registration process would not be reliant on too few people, but high enough that the attester would carry sufficient authority. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In administrative terms, processing and determining applications would be the responsibility of EROs, Returning Officers (ROs)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he prison service would be responsible for attesting forms and providing support to prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> regist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and vot</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A 2008 study found that 60% of prisoners have difficulties in basic literacy skills</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (The Literacy Trust, Literacy Changes Lives – The Role of Literacy in Offending Behaviour, London 2008)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Each prisoner would be responsible for filling in their own electoral registration form, so it is likely that additional support from prison staff in filling in the forms may be required. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">role of the Electoral Commission</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> would be limited to providing guidance to EROs and the prison service on legislative requirements, together with practical advice and information relating to prisoner registration and voting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ndividual electoral registration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">(IER)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current system of electoral registration in Great Britain will be replaced with a system of IER from summer 2014.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">IER will end the system whereby the head of the household is responsible for registering all the other residents on the electoral register. In addition to the requirement for individuals to register </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">themselves, identities will be verified by checking personal identifiers against records held by the Department </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Work and Pensions</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (DWP)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Government intends to simplify the transition to IER by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enabling</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> EROs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to check their electoral registration records against other sources of public data (such as DWP records) as a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">way of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">verifying the details of electors who are already on the electoral register. Individuals who cannot be ‘confirmed’ in this way will </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be required to make an application to register individually and provide personal identifiers (date of birth and National Insurance Number), which can then be verified.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Any move to enfranchise prisoners </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">would </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">therefore need to take into account the potential impact of IER on the ability of prisoners to register to vote. Issues to consider would include:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nsuring that prisoners are able to access personal information (such as their National Insurance Number) for the purposes of registering to vote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nsuring that there is an accessible exceptions process in place for those prisoners who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> cannot obtain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> this information</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he need to raise awareness about </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the practical requirements for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prisoners register</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to vote under the new system.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there any evidence to suggest that allowing prisoners to vote would have a significant impact on particular constituencies? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We do </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">have any </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specific or detailed </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evidence that would enable us to </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">reach any conclusions about whether allowing prisoners to vote would have a significant impact on particular constituencies</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. Evidence would need to come from </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">relevant </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">research about </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the background and demographics of </span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prisoners rather than research about electoral registration, and this is not an area in which we have expertise.</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> We note, however, that if prisoners were registered at the address where they are detained, it is possible that they could constitute a significant proportion of the electorate for a given ward (or, to a lesser degree, constituency</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="color:#222222; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">We believe</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> therefore</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that prisoners should be registered at</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> either</span><span style="color:#000000; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a previous or intended address in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What lessons can be drawn from the experience of other countries regarding prisoner voting?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n practical terms, countries that allow prisoner voting adopt a range of strategies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">while Australia, Canada, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Germany, New Zealand and South Africa do allow prisoner</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s serving short </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">sentences to vote, none of these countries</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> allow proxy voting at national </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">elections (for prisoners or non-prisoners). I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nstead, either postal voting is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">used, or, in Australia where voting is compu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">lsory, election officials visit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the prison to collect ballot papers. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">However, in France, Belgium and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Luxembourg proxy voting is the only me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">thod that imprisoned voters can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">use to cast a ballot. The consistent facto</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">r is that where proxy voting is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">allowed for those unable to attend the polling station, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that facility is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">extended to prisoner voters.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">With regard to pris</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oner registration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> New Zealand i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ncorporates prison voters under the rubric of advance voting procedures. The prison management supplies the local </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">RO</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for the electorate in which the prison is situated </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a list of prisoners who are entitled to vote and wish to do so. This list is then checked against the electoral roll to check whether the prisoner is enrolled. Prisoners who are not enrolled but wish to be so can enrol on the day they vote, when special teams visit the prisons to facilitate the process of voting. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:8.35pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In Australia, eligible prisoners could register to vote in Federal elections</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the area in which they began their sentence or in an area in which they could establish at least four legally defined associations. It should be noted that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">since </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2006 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">risoners have been denied the right to vote in Federal elections. As we have stated above, we do not consider the process of tying prisoner registration to the location of the prison </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s appropriate to the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:none">June 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>